ical grounds. Scientifically—because we cannot trust the precision of 10,000-year predictions that promise containment of the waste. Ethically—because geological disposal ignores the rights of present and future generations to equal treatment, due process, and free informed consent.Shrader-Frechette focuses her argument on the world's first proposed high-level radioactive waste facility at Yucca Mountain, Nevada. Analyzing a mass of technical literature, she demonstrates the weaknesses in the professional risk-assessors' arguments that claim the site is sufficiently safe for such a plan. We should postpone the question of geological disposal for at least a century and use monitored, retrievable, above-ground storage of the waste until then. Her message regarding radwaste is clear: what you can't see can hurt you.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRadioactive waste disposal in the groundxEnvironmental aspects. 0aRadioactive waste disposal in the groundxRisk assessment. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  aconsent.  adue process.  aethics.  ageology.  agovernment.  ahalf life.  ahealth and safety.  alegal issues.  aliability.  amorals.  anatural history.  anatural world.  anevada.  anuclear power.  anuclear waste.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apollution.  apublic health.  aradioactive waste.  aradwaste.  arespiratory illness.  ascience.  ascientific.  aunited states history.  aus government.  aus history.  ayucca mountain.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008244140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091396740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520913967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97805209